This is a tragedy for all involved.
It must however, be remembered that she was found guilty of dangerous driving, not of using the phone. There are many things that can (and do) distract road users. Using a phone may be one but noticing the young lady in the short skirt or the latest Ferrari going the other way can be equally as bad. The "education" that is required is for people to understand how to manage such distractions while driving. If anyone on here can claim to have successfully achieved that for 100% of the time then:
a) Please tell everyone else how you managed it;
b) Please stop lying to both yourself and us;
I am 100% sure the driver in this did not go out with the intention of hurting or killing another road user. She made a big mistake and someone died. A court, which has been specifically appointed to judge such situations has decided on the appropriate punishment. No one wins!

You know, I might just become a repugnican if it means I can click on a news link without it autoplaying video.
